<br>
Someone asked me to think about what the &quot;choice&quot; of being homosexual does to your life.  I want you to know, whoever that was back on page 3 of this thread, that I have thought about it and this is what I've decided I believe:<br>
<br>
Homosexuality is a choice.  You asked if people would really make the choice to be gay considering all the problems that would cause them to have in their life.  I say yes.  People for thousands of years have made choices that have made them the target of persecution.  The easiest example of this is Christians in Roman times.  They chose to be Christian, knowing what the consequences would be, they chose not to hide the fact that they were christian, still knowing what the choices would be, and they lived (or died) by that decision.<br>
<br>
The fact that there are consequences to our choices does not negate the fact that they are still choices we make.  I did not chose to be raised Christian, but I was.  And when the time came for me to make the choice to either continue down that path, or to walk another, I chose.<br>
<br>
In the same vein, people are raised how they are raised (though i accept the fact that very few people are actually raised gay) and when the time comes for them to choose how to live their sexual life, they choose.<br>
<br>
The fact that most of us chose our sexuality during a very emotional time of our lives probably does not help things.  Adolescence (sp) is probably the WORST time for people to make choices that are going to affect them for the rest of their life, but that is the time when we start feeling our sexuality and, therefore, the time we usually choose which sex we find attractive.  I think this is illustrated in the fact that some people find themselves attracted to BOTH sexes during adolescence (sp again) and only through experimentation are they able to choose which sex they want.  I think this is further illustrated by the fact that some people never choose between either but, rather, continue to be attracted to both.<br>
<br>
I take into account that our upbringing is a huge factor in our sexuality, as it is a factor in everything.  But I think until some geninisist (sp again... dictionary.com wont load NOOOOOOO) finds the &quot;sexuality&quot; gene and shows us that sexuality is, in fact, geneticly predisposed I will continue to believe that our sexuality is as much a choice as our religious belief.<br>
<br>
